overview: >-
  The user initiated a request to resolve a wide array of issues within a pull
  request, ranging from critical security vulnerabilities like forgeable admin
  cookies and unvalidated API parameters to various functional bugs affecting
  PDF generation, form inputs, and UI elements. The agent began by thoroughly
  reviewing the PR comments, CI status, and relevant code, identifying both
  existing problems and local fixes that hadn't been pushed.

  The core of the work involved systematically addressing each issue. This
  included replacing an insecure 'true' cookie with a robust HMAC-signed session
  system, implementing input validation and pagination for API endpoints to
  prevent abuse and memory issues, and refining PDF generation logic to
  correctly handle empty time inputs and include minute-level detail. UI
  improvements included enabling null values for number fields and activating
  the "Download PDF" button. Additionally, Zod schema validation was enhanced
  with regex for time fields.

  A significant challenge arose with a build warning concerning Node.js
  module usage in the Edge Runtime-based middleware, which was critical for
  Vercel deployments. The agent proactively refactored the authentication module
  to leverage the Web Crypto API, ensuring compatibility and maintaining
  security. After these comprehensive fixes, local lint and TypeScript checks
  passed, and GitHub Actions builds succeeded. However, at the conversation's
  conclusion, Vercel deploys were still failing, indicating further
  investigation into the deployment environment was necessary.
